    <div class=3D"c-wysiwyg c-post-content__wysiwyg">
       =20
<p><strong><em>In this guest post, Ultralytics, creators of the popular YOL=
O (You Only Look Once) family of convolutional neural networks, share their=
 insights on deploying and running their powerful AI models on Raspberry Pi=
 devices, offering solutions for a wide range of real-world problems.</em><=
/strong></p>



<p>Computer vision is redefining industries by enabling machines to process=
 and understand visual data like images and videos. To truly grasp the impa=
ct of vision AI, consider this: <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/mod=
els/">Ultralytics YOLO models</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralyt=
ics.com/models/yolov8/">Ultralytics YOLOv8</a> and the newly launched <a hr=
ef=3D"https://github.com/ultralytics/ultralytics?tab=3Dreadme-ov-file">Ultr=
alytics YOLO11</a>, which support computer vision tasks like <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.ultralytics.com/blog/the-evolution-of-object-detection-and-ultraly=
tics-yolo-models">object detection</a> and <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralyt=
ics.com/tasks/classify/">image classification</a>, have been used over <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DrfI5vOo3-_A&amp;t=3D23848s">100 bi=
llion times</a>. There are 500 to 600 million uses every day and thousands =
of uses every second across applications like <a href=3D"https://www.ultral=
ytics.com/blog/understanding-the-integration-of-computer-vision-in-robotics=
">robotics</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/computer-vision=
-in-agriculture-transforming-fruit-detection-and-precision-farming">agricul=
ture</a>, and more.</p>



<div style=3D"height:20px" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"wp-block-spacer"><=
/div>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><img fetchpriority=3D"high" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"1024" height=3D"576" src=3D"https://www.raspberrypi.c=
om/app/uploads/2024/11/unnamed-1-1024x576.png" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-1=
13355"><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">YOLO can be used in the agr=
iculture sector</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<p>To take this a step further, Ultralytics has partnered with Raspberry Pi=
 to bring vision AI to one of the most accessible and versatile computing p=
latforms. This collaboration makes it possible to <a href=3D"https://docs.u=
ltralytics.com/guides/model-deployment-options/">deploy YOLO models</a> dir=
ectly on Raspberry Pi, enabling real-time computer vision applications in a=
 compact, cost-effective, and easy-to-use way.</p>



<p>By supporting such integrations, Ultralytics aims to enhance model compa=
tibility across diverse deployment environments. For instance, the <a href=
=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/integrations/sony-imx500/">Sony IMX500</a>=
, the intelligent vision sensor with on-sensor AI processing capabilities i=
ncluded in the Raspberry Pi AI Camera, works with Raspberry Pi to run YOLO =
models, enabling advanced edge AI applications.</p>



<p>In this article, we=E2=80=99ll explore how <a href=3D"https://docs.ultra=
lytics.com/models/yolo11/">YOLO models</a> can be deployed on Raspberry Pi =
devices, look at real-world use cases, and highlight the benefits of this e=
xciting collaboration for vision AI projects. Let=E2=80=99s get started!</p=
>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Enabling edge AI solutions with Raspberry Pi=
 and Ultralytics YOLO</h2>



<p>Raspberry Pi is an affordable and widely used device, making it a great =
choice for <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/modes/export/">deploying=
 </a>vision AI models like YOLO. Running Ultralytics YOLO models on Raspber=
ry Pi enables real-time <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/tasks/">com=
puter vision capabilities</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.=
com/tasks/detect/">object detection</a>, directly on the device, eliminatin=
g the need for cloud resources. Local processing reduces latency and improv=
es privacy, making it ideal for applications where speed and data security =
are essential.</p>



<p>Ultralytics offers optimized models, like <a href=3D"https://www.ultraly=
tics.com/blog/all-you-need-to-know-about-ultralytics-yolo11-and-its-applica=
tions">YOLO11</a>, that can run efficiently on relatively resource-constrai=
ned devices, with the Nano and Small model variants providing the best perf=
ormance on lower-power hardware. Leveraging these optimized models on Raspb=
erry Pi devices is easy with the <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/gu=
ides/raspberry-pi/">Ultralytics Python API or CLI</a>, ensuring smooth depl=
oyment and operation. In addition to this, Ultralytics also supports automa=
ted <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/guides/model-testing/">testing<=
/a> for Raspberry Pi devices on GitHub Actions to regularly check for bugs =
and ensure the models are ready for deployment.</p>



<p>Another interesting feature of the Ultralytics YOLO models is that they =
can be exported in various formats (as shown in the image below), including=
 <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/integrations/ncnn/">NCNN</a> (Neur=
al Network Compression and Optimization). Designed for devices with relativ=
ely constrained computing power, such as Raspberry Pi=E2=80=99s ARM64 archi=
tecture, NCNN ensures faster inference times by <a href=3D"https://www.ultr=
alytics.com/blog/what-is-model-optimization-a-quick-guide">optimizing model=
 weights</a> and activations through techniques like <a href=3D"https://www=
.ultralytics.com/glossary/model-quantization">quantization</a>.</p>



<div style=3D"height:20px" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"wp-block-spacer"><=
/div>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><img decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1=
024" height=3D"604" src=3D"https://www.raspberrypi.com/app/uploads/2024/11/=
unnamed-3-1024x604.png" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-113353"><figcaption clas=
s=3D"wp-element-caption">Benchmarking Ultralytics YOLO11 inferencing On Ras=
pberry Pi</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Raspberry Pi, Sony IMX500, and YOLO for real=
-time AI applications</h2>



<p>The Raspberry Pi AI Camera is a perfect example of how this integration =
helps support compatibility across a range of deployment environments. Its =
<a href=3D"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Di-zGog0uzZ4&amp;list=3DPL1FZnk=
j4ad1MrjyuouYyvnBEhCImF2OOx&amp;index=3D3&amp;t=3D794s">IMX500</a> intellig=
ent vision sensor comes with on-sensor AI processing, allowing it to analyz=
e visual data directly and output metadata rather than raw images. While th=
e IMX500 is powerful on its own, it needs to be paired with a device like R=
aspberry Pi to run YOLO models effectively. In this setup, a Raspberry Pi a=
cts as the host device, facilitating communication with the AI Camera and e=
nabling real-time AI applications powered by YOLO.</p>



<div style=3D"height:20px" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"wp-block-spacer"><=
/div>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><img decoding=3D"async" width=3D"10=
00" height=3D"667" src=3D"https://www.raspberrypi.com/app/uploads/2024/11/u=
nnamed-2.png" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-113354"><figcaption class=3D"wp-el=
ement-caption">Raspberry Pi AI Camera incorporates the Sony IMX500</figcapt=
ion></figure>
</div>


<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Real-world examples of YOLO applications on =
Raspberry Pi</h2>



<p>Raspberry Pi, combined with the Ultralytics YOLO models, unlocks countle=
ss possibilities for real-world applications. This collaboration bridges th=
e gap between experimental AI setups and production-ready solutions, offeri=
ng an affordable, scalable, and practical tool for a wide range of industri=
es.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Here are a few impactful use cases:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/from-algorithms-to-automati=
on-ais-role-in-robotics"><strong>Robotics</strong></a>: YOLO can enable <a =
href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/tesla-autonomous-cybercab-and-the-=
future-of-ai-in-robotics">robots</a> to navigate environments, recognize ob=
jects, and perform tasks with precision, making them more autonomous and ef=
ficient</li>



<li><a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/computer-vision-cameras-and=
-their-applications"><strong>Drones</strong></a>: With YOLO running on Rasp=
berry Pi, drones can detect obstacles, track objects, and perform <a href=
=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/shattering-the-surveillance-status-quo=
-with-vision-ai">surveillance</a> in real-time, enhancing their capabilitie=
s in industries like delivery and security</li>



<li><a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/quality-inspection-in-manuf=
acturing-traditional-vs-deep-learning-methods"><strong>Quality control in m=
anufacturing</strong></a>: YOLO can help identify defects in production lin=
es, ensuring higher quality standards with automated inspection</li>



<li><a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/from-farm-to-table-how-ai-d=
rives-innovation-in-agriculture"><strong>Smart farming</strong></a>: By usi=
ng YOLO to monitor <a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/top-10-benef=
its-of-using-vision-ai-for-agriculture">crop health</a> and <a href=3D"http=
s://www.ultralytics.com/blog/object-detection-for-pest-control">detect pest=
s</a>, farmers can make data-driven decisions, improving yields and reducin=
g resource waste</li>
</ul>



<div style=3D"height:20px" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"wp-block-spacer"><=
/div>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Benefits of running Ultralytics YOLO models =
on Raspberry Pi for edge AI</h2>



<p>There are many advantages to deploying YOLO models on Raspberry Pi, maki=
ng it a practical and affordable option for edge AI applications. For insta=
nce, performance can be boosted by using hardware accelerators like <a href=
=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/guides/coral-edge-tpu-on-raspberry-pi/">Go=
ogle Coral Edge TPU</a>, enabling faster and more efficient real-time proce=
ssing.</p>



<div style=3D"height:20px" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"wp-block-spacer"><=
/div>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><img decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1=
024" height=3D"674" src=3D"https://www.raspberrypi.com/app/uploads/2024/11/=
unnamed-1024x674.png" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-113356"><figcaption class=
=3D"wp-element-caption">Coral Edge TPU connected to a Raspberry Pi</figcapt=
ion></figure>
</div>


<p>Here are some of the other key benefits:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Scalability</strong>: The setup can be extended to multiple dev=
ices, making it a great choice for larger projects such as factory automati=
on or smart city systems</li>



<li><strong>Flexibility</strong>: YOLO=E2=80=99s compatibility ensures that=
 developers can create solutions that work seamlessly across a variety of h=
ardware setups, offering versatility for different applications</li>



<li><strong>Community and support</strong>: With extensive <a href=3D"https=
://docs.ultralytics.com/">resources</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.youtube.com=
/@Ultralytics">tutorials</a>, and an <a href=3D"https://community.ultralyti=
cs.com/">active community</a>, Ultralytics provides the support needed for =
smooth deployment and troubleshooting of YOLO models on Raspberry Pi</li>
</ul>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">To the edge and beyond with Ultralytics YOLO=
 and Raspberry Pi</h2>



<p>YOLO and Raspberry Pi are making edge AI applications more accessible, i=
mpactful, and transformative than ever before. By putting together the adva=
nced capabilities of Ultralytics YOLO models with the cost-effectiveness an=
d flexibility of Raspberry Pi, this partnership allows developers, research=
ers, and hobbyists to bring innovative ideas to life.&nbsp;</p>



<p>With support for devices like the Raspberry Pi AI Camera and scalable ha=
rdware options, this collaboration unlocks opportunities across industries,=
 from robotics and agriculture to manufacturing and beyond.</p>



